Question: We need to take an urgent supervisory decision against a bank to
  prevent damage to the financial system, but normal hearings and
  meeting timelines are too slow. What flexibility is available
  regarding the right to be heard and the non-objection procedure
  itself?
Example answer: In the case of an urgent decision necessary to prevent significant
  damage to the financial system, the ECB may adopt a supervisory
  decision adversely affecting the rights of the addressee without
  giving it the opportunity to comment beforehand; the hearing is then
  postponed and organised as soon as possible after adoption, with a
  clear justification provided in the decision. Under the emergency
  procedure for non-objection, deadlines for written procedures may be
  adjusted, a Supervisory Board meeting may be organised at short
  notice including by teleconference with a 50% quorum, and a shorter
  deadline may be requested of the Governing Council, which may even
  convene immediately after a Supervisory Board meeting. (ECB
  Supervisory Manual, pages 21, 24)
Predicted answer: Key flexibilities available in an urgent situation:  - Waive prior
  hearing: the ECB may adopt a supervisory decision that adversely
  affects the addressee without giving them the opportunity to comment
  beforehand. The hearing is postponed and the decision must contain a
  clear justification for the postponement. - Post-adoption hearing
  and documentation: organise the hearing as soon as possible after
  adoption; when the decision is adopted the assessment of any
  comments must be annexed. - Shorten hearing period: the usual
  two‑week hearing can be shortened in particular circumstances to a
  minimum of three working days. - Shorten written/non‑objection
  deadlines: deadlines for written procedures (and the non‑objection
  procedure) can be adjusted/shortened in emergency cases—subject to
  applicable legal deadlines. - Fast Supervisory Board action: call a
  Supervisory Board meeting at short notice (teleconference is
  allowed); use an extraordinary meeting and, if announced, decisions
  can be taken without regard to the usual quorum requirement. -
  Involve the Governing Council quickly: the Supervisory Board may
  request a shorter non‑objection deadline from the Governing Council,
  which may even convene immediately after the Supervisory Board
  meeting.  Practical checklist: ensure you document a clear
  justification for bypassing the prior hearing, check and respect any
  binding legal time limits, call an emergency SB meeting
  (teleconference/extraordinary), request an accelerated non‑objection
  from the Governing Council, and plan to hold the postponed hearing
  and annex the assessment of comments to the decision as soon as
  possible.
