  data submitted by SIs, and what supervisory action can a JST take if
  a quarterly data quality report flags significant issues?
Example answer: The data quality assessment at the ECB is performed against five
  dimensions: punctuality (lag between the required submission date
  and the actual submission), accuracy (closeness of reported values
  to the underlying supervisory concept), completeness (availability
  of the required information), reliability (closeness of revised
  values to the initially released ones) and plausibility (detection
  of outliers via time-series and peer comparisons). If a quarterly
  data quality report shows significant data quality issues and, after
  a proportionate analysis, the JST detects violations of regulatory
  requirements, the JST takes supervisory action, which may take the
  form of an operational act addressed to the supervised entity,
  arrangements to meet the institution's management, or a proposal to
  use supervisory powers addressed to the Supervisory Board and the
  Governing Council, with the results also likely to be fed into the
  risk assessment of the supervised entity. (ECB Supervisory Manual,
  pages 68, 69)
