Question: Under what circumstances may the ECB become directly involved in the
  supervision of LSIs?
Example answer: The ECB may become involved in the direct supervision of LSIs in some
  specific cases as outlined in the SSM Framework Regulation,
  including taking over supervisory activities to ensure the
  consistent application of high supervisory standards or to follow up
  on a specific request by the NCA. Ultimately, the ECB also becomes
  responsible for direct supervision if the status of an institution
  changes from being an LSI to an SI as a result of a significance
  assessment. (ECB Supervisory Manual, page 115)
Predicted answer: The ECB may become directly involved in the supervision of LSIs (i)
  when an LSI’s financial situation deteriorates or in crisis
  situations prompting intensified oversight and crisis‑management
  activities, (ii) when an LSI is reclassified to an SI following a
  significance assessment (entailing direct takeover), and (iii) when
  an LSI is classified as high‑risk/high‑impact leading to increased
  reporting, oversight and ECB coordination at critical points
  (including decisions on common procedures such as qualifying
